11 CLARIFY SPECIES SUSCEPTIBLE TO CHRONIC WASTING DISEASE
12 SECTION 8. G.S. 106-549.97 reads as rewritten:
13 "§ 106-549.97. Regulation by Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services of farmed
14 cervids produced and sold for commercial purposes; definitions.
15 (a) Repealed by Session Laws 2015-263, s. 14(a), effective September 30, 2015.
16 (a1) The following definitions apply in this Article:
17 (1) Commission. – The North Carolina Wildlife Resources Commission.
18 (2) Department. – The North Carolina Department of Agriculture and Consumer
19 Services.
20 (3) Farmed Cervid. – Any cervid, as defined by the USDA Standards, that is
21 susceptible to Chronic Wasting Disease, or any other member of the Cervidae
22 family that is not susceptible to Chronic Wasting Disease, that is held in
23 captivity and produced, bought, or sold for commercial purposes. Cervids that
24 are susceptible to Chronic Wasting Disease are those set forth in 9 C.F.R. §
25 55.1. With regard to cervids that are susceptible to Chronic Wasting Disease,
26 the term "farmed cervid" shall only include any cervid that was bred in
27 captivity and has been continuously maintained within a herd that is enrolled
28 in and complies with a USDA-approved Herd Certification Program. Any
29 animal registered or tagged in any licensed captive cervid facility existing
30 within the State as of July 1, 2015, is deemed to be a farmed cervid.
31 (4) Non-Farmed Cervid. – All animals in the family Cervidae other than farmed
32 cervids.
33 (5) USDA. – The United States Department of Agriculture.
34 (6) USDA Standards. – The United States Department of Agriculture's Chronic
35 Wasting Disease Program Standards, May 2014 edition, and subsequent
36 updates.
37 (a2) The Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services shall regulate the production,
38 sale, possession, and transportation, including importation and exportation, of farmed cervids.
39 The Department shall have sole authority with regard to farmed cervids, including administration
40 of the North Carolina Captive Cervid Herd Certification Program. The Department shall allow
41 the sale of farmed cervids, whether alive or dead, whole or in part, including, but not limited to,
42 the sale of antlers, antler velvet, hides, or meat from captive populations of farmed cervids. The
43 Department shall follow the USDA Standards and the provisions set forth in 9 C.F.R. Part 55 and
44 9 C.F.R. Part 81 in the implementation of this Article with regard to cervids susceptible to
45 Chronic Wasting Disease. The Department may adopt rules to implement this Article, including,
46 but not limited to, requirements for captivity licenses, captivity permits, transportation permits,
47 importation permits, and exportation permits. The Department may issue new captivity licenses
48 or permits for farmed cervid facilities that will hold cervids susceptible to Chronic Wasting
49 Disease only if Chronic Wasting Disease-susceptible source animals are from a certified herd in
50 accordance with USDA Standards from an existing licensed facility. Nothing in this section shall
51 limit the Department's ability to issue new captivity licenses and permits for farmed cervid
Page 4 Senate Bill 639-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 facilities that will hold cervids that are not susceptible to Chronic Wasting Disease. Any cervid
2 that is not susceptible to Chronic Wasting Disease as set forth in 9 C.F.R. § 55.1 may be imported
3 into the State to any licensed captive cervid facility. The Department shall not issue an
4 importation permit for any farmed cervid from a Chronic Wasting Disease-positive, exposed, or
5 suspect farmed cervid facility. Until such time as the USDA has adopted an approved method of
6 testing for Chronic Wasting Disease in living cervids, cervids susceptible to Chronic Wasting
7 Disease shall not be imported into North Carolina.
8 …."
