10 (1) For an improperly marked shellfish lease area, a first offense shall be
11 punishable only by issuance of a warning ticket pursuant to G.S. 113-140. A
12 second offense within one month of the issuance of a warning ticket shall be
13 punishable as an infraction as provided in G.S. 14-3.1. A third offense within
14 one month of the issuance of a warning ticket shall be punishable as a Class 3
15 misdemeanor.
16 (2) For operating under an expired aquaculture operation permit, if the violation
17 occurs within one month of the expiration of the permit, the violation shall be
18 punishable only by issuance of a warning ticket pursuant to G.S. 113-140.
19 (3) For operating under an expired shellfish lease agreement, if the violation
20 occurs within one month of the expiration of the agreement, the violation shall
21 be punishable only by issuance of a warning ticket pursuant to G.S. 113-140."
22 SECTION 16.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
23 offenses committed on or after that date.
24
25 DACS LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICER JURISDICTION
26 SECTION 17. G.S. 106-900 reads as rewritten:
27 "§ 106-900. Powers of Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services law-enforcement
28 officers.
29 (a) Authorization to Appoint. – The Commissioner is authorized to appoint as many
30 Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services law enforcement officers as he or she deems
31 necessary to investigate and enforce any violation of the laws within the authority of the
32 Department or which occur on Department property. necessary. Such officers shall meet the
33 requirements of Article 1 of Chapter 17C of the General Statutes and shall take the oath of office
34 prescribed by Section 7 of Article VI of the North Carolina Constitution. Of these officers, the
35 Commissioner may designate certain officers to also have the powers and the duties of a forest
36 ranger enumerated in G.S. 106-898 and G.S. 106-899 and the power to enforce the forest laws.
37 A Department law enforcement officer may arrest, without warrant, any person or persons
38 committing any crime in the officer's presence or who such officer has probable cause for
39 believing has committed a crime in the officer's presence and bring such person or persons
40 forthwith before a district court or other officer having jurisdiction. Department law enforcement
41 officers shall also have authority to obtain and serve warrants including warrants for violation of
42 any duly promulgated rule of the Department.
43 (b) Territorial Jurisdiction. – A Department law enforcement officer is a State officer
44 with jurisdiction throughout the State, and beyond its boundaries to the extent provided by law,
45 in enforcing all matters within his or her respective subject matter jurisdiction as set forth in this
46 section.
47 (c) Subject Matter Jurisdiction. – After taking the oath described in subsection (a) of this
48 section, a Department law enforcement officer shall have the authority to arrest and take other
49 investigatory and enforcement actions for any criminal offense meeting any of the following
50 criteria:
Page 10 Senate Bill 639-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Occurring, encountered, or otherwise discovered on the premises of, or
2 elsewhere when the conduct relates to, property owned by, leased to, or
3 managed by the Department.
4 (2) Provided for under this Chapter, including the forest laws as set forth in
5 G.S. 106-897.
6 (3) Provided for in any duly adopted rule of the Department.
7 (4) Encountered or otherwise discovered while investigating or enforcing matters
8 for the Department or encountered or otherwise discovered while
9 investigating or enforcing the provisions of this Chapter, including the forest
10 laws as set forth in G.S. 106-897 and any duly adopted rule of the Department.
11 (5) Encountered or otherwise discovered while carrying out any duty or function
12 assigned to the Department by law.
13 (6) Occurring in a Department law enforcement officer's presence.
14 (7) Occurring outside of a Department law enforcement officer's presence as
15 provided in G.S. 15A-401(b), and for other offenses evincing a flouting of
16 their authority as enforcement officers or constituting a threat to public peace
17 and order which would tend to subvert the authority of the State if ignored. In
18 particular, Department law enforcement officers are authorized to arrest for
19 violations of G.S. 14-223, 14-225, 14-269, and 14-277.
20 (8) When assisting another law enforcement agency.
21 (d) Authority. – Department law enforcement officers have authority as peace officers to
22 do all of the following:
23 (1) Execute criminal process.
24 (2) Obtain and serve warrants, including arrest warrants, search warrants, orders
25 for arrest, criminal summonses, citations, subpoenas, and warrants for
26 violation of any duly adopted rule of the Department, and all other process
27 connected with any cases within their subject matter jurisdiction.
28 (3) Respond to and take enforcement action for any crime of violence or breach
29 of the peace.
30 (4) Any additional duties as may from time to time be directed by the
31 Commissioner when needed for security purposes at a public event or to
32 protect persons or property because of a disaster or state of emergency.
33 (e) Primary Responsibilities. – The primary law enforcement responsibility of a
34 Department law enforcement officer is the enforcement of this Chapter, including the forest laws
35 as set forth in G.S. 106-897 and any duly adopted rule of the Department.
36 (f) Service of Orders. – Department law enforcement officers have the authority to serve
37 and execute notices, orders, or demands issued by the Commissioner, the Department, or the
38 Board of Agriculture relating to any administrative proceeding. While serving and executing such
39 notices, orders, or demands, Department law enforcement officers shall have all of the power and
40 authority possessed by law enforcement officers when executing an arrest warrant.
41 (g) Temporary Stops. – Department law enforcement officers are authorized to stop
42 temporarily any persons they reasonably believe to be engaging in any activity regulated by the
43 Department to determine whether the activity is being conducted in compliance with the law,
44 including license and permitting requirements. Department law enforcement officers are also
45 authorized to see that the provisions of Chapter 20 of the General Statutes are enforced within
46 their jurisdiction and shall have the power to arrest on sight or upon warrant any motor vehicle
47 upon the highways of the State for the purpose of determining whether the motor vehicle is being
48 operated in violation of any of the provisions of Chapter 20 of the General Statutes. If the person
49 stopped is in a motor vehicle being driven at the time and the Department law enforcement officer
50 is also in a motor vehicle, the Department law enforcement officer shall sound a siren or activate
