4 INCREASE PENALTY FOR A SECOND OR SUBSEQUENT OFFENSE FOR
5 LARCENY OF CROPS
6 SECTION 18.(a) G.S. 14-78 reads as rewritten:
7 "§ 14-78. Larceny of ungathered crops.
8 (a) If It is unlawful for any person shall to steal or feloniously take and carry away any
9 maize, corn, wheat, rice or other grain, or any cotton, tobacco, potatoes, peanuts, pulse, fruit,
10 vegetable or other product cultivated for food or market, growing, standing or remaining
11 ungathered in any field or ground, that person is guilty of a Class H felony.ground.
12 (b) A violation of this section is punishable as follows:
13 (1) For a first offense under this section, the person is guilty of a Class H felony,
14 punishable by a fine of not less than two hundred fifty dollars ($250.00) in
15 addition to any other punishment prescribed for the offense.
16 (2) For a second or subsequent offense under this section, the person is guilty of
17 a Class G felony, punishable by a fine of not less than five hundred dollars
18 ($500.00) in addition to any other punishment prescribed for the offense."
19 SECTION 18.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
20 offenses committed on or after that date.
21
22 LIMIT LIABILITY FOR FIFRA-COMPLIANT LABELING
23 SECTION 19.(a) G.S. 99B-5 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
24 "(d) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this section, the duty of a manufacturer or seller of
25 a pesticide to warn a consumer or the public about the risks associated with the pesticide shall be
26 presumed to be satisfied if the pesticide bears the label approved by the United States
27 Environmental Protection Agency under the Federal Insecticide, Fungicide, and Rodenticide Act
28 (FIFRA) (7 U.S.C. § 136 et seq.) and the pesticide is registered with the Pesticide Board pursuant
29 to G.S. 143-442. This presumption may be rebutted only by a showing that the weight of the
30 scientific evidence does not support the scientific basis on which the required warning is
31 premised and that the manufacturer or seller knew or should have known at the time the pesticide
32 was sold that the required warning was not supported by the weight of scientific evidence. At a
33 minimum, evidence to rebut the presumption shall be academically peer reviewed, published in
34 a recognized academic journal, capable of replication, and reflected by a reliable application of
35 scientific principles and methods to the risks associated with the use of the product."
36 SECTION 19.(b) This section is effective when it becomes law and applies to
37 actions filed on or after that date.
38
39 REPEAL THE SALE OF RAW MILK FOR NONHUMAN CONSUMPTION
40 SECTION 20.1.(a) G.S. 106-266.35 reads as rewritten:
41 "§ 106-266.35. Sale or dispensing of milk.
42 (a) Except as provided in subsection (d) of this section:
43 (1) Only milk that is Grade "A" pasteurized milk may be sold or dispensed
44 directly to consumers for human consumption.
45 (2) Raw milk and raw milk products shall be sold or dispensed only to a permitted
46 milk hauler or to a processing facility at which the processing of milk is
47 permitted, graded, or regulated by a local, State, or federal agency.
48 (b) The Board of Agriculture may adopt rules to provide exceptions for dispensing raw
49 milk and raw milk products for nonhuman consumption. Any raw milk or raw milk product
50 dispensed as animal feed shall include on its label the statement "NOT FOR HUMAN
51 CONSUMPTION" in letters at least one-half inch in height. Any raw milk or raw milk product
Page 12 Senate Bill 639-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 dispensed as animal feed shall also include on its label the statement "IT IS NOT LEGAL TO
2 SELL RAW MILK FOR HUMAN CONSUMPTION IN NORTH CAROLINA." This labeling
3 requirement does not apply to raw milk or raw milk products dispensed for personal use or
4 consumption to the independent or partial owner of a cow, goat, or other lactating animal.
5 (c) As used in this section, the term "sale" or "sold" means any transaction that involves
6 the transfer or dispensing of milk and milk products or the right to acquire milk and milk products
7 through barter or contractual arrangement or in exchange for any other form of compensation.
8 The term "sale" or "sold" does not include the transfer or dispensing of raw milk or raw milk
9 products to, or the right to acquire raw milk or raw milk products by, the independent or partial
10 owner of a cow, goat, or other lactating animal.
11 (d) Nothing in this section shall prohibit the dispensing of raw milk or raw milk products
12 for personal use or consumption to, or the acquisition of raw milk or raw milk products for
13 personal use or consumption by, an independent or partial owner of a cow, goat, or other lactating
14 animal."
15 SECTION 20.1.(b) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025.
16
17 ADD CERTAIN COMPOSTING FACILITIES TO THE DEFINITION OF
18 "AGRICULTURE"
19 SECTION 21. G.S. 106-581.1 reads as rewritten:
20 "§ 106-581.1. Agriculture defined.
21 For purposes of this Article, the terms "agriculture", "agricultural", and "farming" refer to all
22 of the following:
23 …
24 (8) The production, processing, storage, use, and sale of compost for agricultural,
25 residential, or commercial purposes by a permitted Small or Large Type 1,
26 Type 2, or Type 3 composting facility as defined in rules adopted by the
27 Environmental Management Commission. For the purposes of this section,
28 compost means a product made from organic plant, animal, or food waste and
29 created through controlled aerobic, biological decomposition of
30 biodegradable materials that, when subject to mesophilic and thermophilic
31 temperatures, stabilizes the carbon content, reduces the viability of pathogens
32 and vector attraction, and when added to soils is beneficial to plant growth."
33
34 PUV BUSINESS ENTITY TEST CHANGES
35 SECTION 21.5.(a) G.S. 105-277.2(4)b. reads as rewritten:
36 "b. A business entity that meets all of the following conditions:
37 1. Its principal business is farming agricultural land, horticultural
38 land, or forestland. When determining whether an applicant
39 under G.S. 105-277.4 has as its principal business farming
40 agricultural land, horticultural land, or forestland, the assessor
41 shall presume the applicant's principal business to be farming
42 agricultural land, horticultural land, or forestland if the
43 applicant has been approved by another county for present-use
44 value taxation for a qualifying property located within the
45 other county; provided, however, the presumption afforded the
46 applicant may be rebutted by the assessor and shall have no
47 bearing on the determination of whether the individual parcel
48 of land meets one or more of the classes defined in
49 G.S. 105-277.3(a). If the assessor is able to rebut the
50 presumption, this shall not invalidate the determination that the
Senate Bill 639-Third Edition Page 13

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 applicant's principal business is farming agricultural land,
2 horticultural land, or forestland in the other county.
3 2. All of its members are, directly or indirectly, individuals who
4 are actively engaged in farming agricultural land, horticultural
5 land, or forestland or a relative of one of the individuals who
6 is actively engaged. Under this condition, "actively engaged"
7 means the members make significant contributions of capital,
8 land, or equipment to the farming operation, and includes
9 leasing land or farm equipment. An individual is indirectly a
10 member of a business entity that owns the land if the individual
11 is a member of a business entity or a beneficiary of a trust that
12 is part of the ownership structure of the business entity that
13 owns the land.
14 3. It is not a corporation whose shares are publicly traded, and
15 none of its members are corporations whose shares are publicly
16 traded.
17 4. If it leases the land, all of its members are individuals and are
18 relatives. Under this condition, "principal business" and
19 "actively engaged" include leasing."
20 SECTION 21.5.(b) This section is effective for taxes imposed for taxable years
21 beginning on or after January 1, 2027.
